Democracy without popular cohesion
Something has happened to democracy in the sense that governments are elected by the people, and this is happening everywhere in the world.
Somehow people have lost faith in elections.
Voter turnout is declining in many countries; in the case of European Parliament elections, the turnout was so low that the legitimacy of the election result is questionable.
Apart from voter turnout, we have come to accept parties or candidates who receive 25% of the cast votes as "winners."
Majority governments are formed based on minorities from Holland to Finland and Japan.
Even the apparent exceptions do not prove the opposite.
Only a few American Presidents were elected by more than 10% of the eligible voters. In fact, half of the eligible voters in the USA do not even register to vote; of those who do register, half do not vote; and of those who do vote, less than half vote for the election winner.
Even Tony Blair's "dam-breaking" majority in the UK House of Commons is shaky: The Labour Party received only slightly over 40% of the votes in the last election in 2002, with a voter turnout of 60%.
Accordingly, only 24% of the total electorate supported Blair's party.
In most countries, elections look quite different today compared to twenty, or even fifty years ago.
What has happened?
That could be because voters no longer trust political parties.
The electoral democracy works in most countries through the mediation of organizations that present candidates standing for specific packages of political options, for a "manifesto" or a "election program."
This well-established practice no longer works for a number of reasons.
Ideological party programs have lost their power; voters no longer accept the packages imposed by the parties, they want to reach out and choose for themselves.
Furthermore, political parties have become machines composed of tightly organized ranks of insiders.
The paradox here is that parties have become even more clique-like despite losing their distinct ideological orientation.
It is more important to belong to them than to share their specific beliefs.
Such developments have distanced the parties from the voters.
Because most people no longer want to belong to any particular party, only a minority is playing the party game.
That suspicion of political parties among the public is thus also heightened, just like in professional sports, where it is expensive to participate.
When the costs are borne by taxpayers, this is taken badly.
But without financial support from the state, parties would have to find money through channels that are often dubious, if not outright illegal.
Many of the major political scandals of the last decades involved the financing of parties and their candidates.
And other indicators, such as the clear decline in memberships, confirm that the parties have become unpopular.
Parties are indispensable for an electoral democracy.
The result is a clear separation between visible political actors and the electorate.
Because parties are active in parliaments, the effects of this separation impact one of the key institutions of democracy.
People no longer believe that parliaments represent them and thus possess the necessary legitimacy to make decisions on their behalf.
At this point, another fairly independent development comes into play.
People are today more impatient than ever before.
As consumers, they expect immediate satisfaction.
However, as voters, they have to wait before they feel the results of the election they cast at the ballot box.
Sometimes they never see the desired results.
Democracy needs time not only for elections, but also for discussions and thoughtful consideration.
The consumer as a voter, however, does not want to accept this and therefore turns away.
There are alternatives, but each has its own problems as a democratic solution.
Direct actions through demonstrations have become a regular and often effective event.
For less mobile people, it could be replaced by the possibility of expressing their opinion electronically; this ranges from internet discussion pages to electronic messages to political leaders.
Then there are non-governmental organizations. They often have undemocratic internal structures, yet seem to be more closely connected to the citizens.
Furthermore, of course, there is the option to completely disconnect and leave politics to the experts, focusing instead on other aspects of life.
This entails the greatest risks, as it fosters the creeping authoritarianism that is a hallmark of our time.
But even the other signs of the separation between politics and citizens create a rather insecure situation, because no one can anymore say how representative the prevailing views are.
Some want to address the issue through more direct democracy.
But maintaining a持续...uemove the context to English directly.
There would be much to argue for holding on to the classical institutions of parliamentary democracy and trying to reconnect them more closely with the citizenry.
Unlikely unpopular parties and declining voter turnout could turn out to be only a temporary phenomenon.
New parties could emerge and infuse elections and representative governments with new life.
But that may not be sufficient to restore the general legitimacy that elected governments have lost.
Therefore, the first concern of all who hold the constitution of freedom dear must be to rethink democracy and its institutions.
